Episode 147: Kris Rugloski

Kris just completed one of the most outrageous years of racing, both in terms of how many races she ran and how many different types of races she excelled in. We gave up trying to guess how she pulls it off and just decided to ask her.

“Of all the events you do, what’s your favorite, what would you chose to do if you could only do one?”

It’s not about the events. It’s about waking up every day grateful for life and health, working everyday to find, create, and grow into the best version of myself. 

Some days that’s a weekend in LA of playing on the beach, Hyrox, and a spartan race. 
And sometimes by Monday I can’t walk down the stairs without pain. 

The best part? Everybody’s best is going to look different, but nobody has reached their full potential. There’s always more- physically and mentally 🔥

Feeling like I finally made it out of a figurative and slightly literal hibernation this winter. This southern gal was not ready for a real winter in Colorado, but I think I thawed out in Dubai last week and I’ll survive after all! ☀️🌲

HYROX- the sport that chews me up and spits me out more than any other, yet somehow I can’t get enough of 🙃
It’s been an interesting start to the year, and finding my way back to what Hyrox strength looks like for me now. 
From a 1:11 in Chicago, to a 1:09 in Houston, to finally hitting a 1:05 in Dallas- all within the span of 5 weeks, I’m happy with the work I’ve put in and the progress I’m seeing!

I didn’t do much running over the winter, but I did a lot of reading- and this sentiment from Scott Hamilton’s book “Finish First” has really stuck with me:
—
“We do not get to choose all of the opportunities that come our way. We do not get to choose our entire path. But we do get to choose what to do with setbacks and opportunities that come our way. We do get to choose how we behave as we wait to know what is coming next. We do get to decide that no matter what happens, we will be ready. Are you willing to have a good attitude even when things aren’t going your way? This is the attitude of a winner.”
—-
Glad to finally be closer to “winning” in my Hyrox fitness, but more importantly doing my best to “win” in my life and passions, both in sport and apart from it 🤗 
—-
#hyrox #hyroxamerica #mysport #fitter #faster #readytogo

Double race weekend on tap!
I’ll be at @spartanrace Big Bear 3k series race on Friday afternoon, then ✈️ to Maryland for the 3rd race in the @savagerace points series on Saturday morning! 

Last year I raced at both locations- but a whole week apart. Landed a 🥇 and a 🥉, any predictions on how I do this weekend!? 

You can catch both these races live feed on @theocrreport YouTube channel… check out their page for more details. 

And- who will I see out there!!? Ready to race the weekend away! 🏃🏼‍♀️

Hard to put this past weekend into words, but I guess we’ll start from the beginning! 

Raced my first @spartanrace North American Elite Series 3k on Friday evening in Big Bear, CA- came into this excited to race against the best in the sport for the first time since last year, try out this new short course format, and see where my fitness put me. 

Really enjoyed the 1k laps to qualify in, running fast and doing a series of obstacles in about 10 minutes is a rush! 

Qualified my way into the final, and despite the heavy carry intensive course, stayed pretty consistent through the 3k lapped format and brought home the W! 

Happy to see my strength, running, and abilities as an athlete continue to improve, and super proud of all the women that took on this course especially @allytippetts_flipper and @idamathildee filling out the podium! 

Will be back for the next series race out east in July, and hope to be ready for whatever course @spartan decides to throw at us then!

Turns out I will do just about anything to make it to a @savagerace! 🪓 

After racing Friday evening, I drove 3 hrs to the airport, ended up having to switch flights after my original flight got delayed, and took off at 11:30 for the other side of the country! 

Landed in Maryland at 7a local time, and on a few hours of airplane sleep made the 1 hr drive to the venue, popped a couple caffeine pills and was ready to race by 9a!

Ran in 2nd and 3rd for most of the race, just trying to keep in contact with the front runners and trading back and forth with @miranda.kielpinski as we took turns messing up on obstacles 🤪 
Wasn’t until the final 4 obstacles, after catching back up to Alex that I was able to make the pass with some obstacle efficiency and take the win by just under 40 secs! Congrats to @jme.ocr.chick also, racing steady and finishing strong at the end! 💪🏽 

I’ve done a handful of crazy race/travel weekends, but this one definitely took the cake. 🍰 Grateful for logistics working out just right to be able to make it happen- and for my body being able to handle everything. Really enjoyed getting to see so many friends and new friends from the community crushing it on both sides of the country…. But also enjoyed getting a solid 10 hrs of sleep Saturday night 😴

Do all the things that make you just you! 

Make the time for things that matter to you. 
Put in the work and effort that no one else is. 
Grow when it hurts. 
Be kind when others aren’t. 
Commit to things that scare you. 
Just because nobody else is doing it may be the best reason for you to. 
Action cures fear. 🤗 

“The most difficult thing is the decision to act, the rest is merely tenacity. The fears are paper tigers. You can do anything you decide to do. You can act to change and control your life; and the procedure, the process is its own reward.” - Amelia Earhart

Thanks to @davidmagida  @brakkenkraker and @theocrreport for this audio clip, @joshinhd for the video, and my friend @kaylakm for making this reel 🤩

I thought of my grandpa as I finished Friday’s Spartan race- just over a year ago I won my first Hyrox event at Dallas on his birthday, and every time I hear my name announced over the speakers I think about how grateful I am for my family and to be a Rugloski. 

I don’t think he ever really fully understood my races, but he never failed to call almost every week to ask me about my last race and wish me luck on the next one.  He had a stroke and passed away a week ago, and while I’ll miss his calls and all the stories he always had to share, I’m grateful for the tough but caring and kind man that’s influenced my life. ❤️

I don’t post much about my day job out of respect for these two little guys’ privacy, but I’m coming up on 1 year now of helping two of the best parents I know raise my two tiny best friends 🥰 

I appreciate the balance that ordinary and simple days with these two smart, funny, beautiful babes exploring and experiencing the world around them brings to my otherwise hectic life of adventures and competing. 

“What do we want more of in life? That’s the question. It’s not accomplishments. It’s not popularity. It’s moments when we feel like we are enough.” —Ryan Holiday

In all the chasing of goals, experiences, and accomplishments, I hope to never forget the things I’m passionate about and that bring me joy and fulfillment 🤗 

@laura_joch #athlete #nannylife

I am Iron(wo)Man! 🦾🦿That was fun! More to come later. But for now, gotta drive home and get some sleep! #ironman #ironwoman #cdaironman

2.4 mile swim
112 mile bike
26.2 mile run
🏊‍♀️ 🚴🏼 🏃🏼‍♀️ 
140.6 miles makes this Ironman the longest distance I’ve covered in a day, and somehow I even enjoyed the majority of it! 
I think this was the biggest test of my theory that “fitness is fitness” and that with a good base it carries over even to areas or events you don’t specifically train for. 
I’m not a swimmer, but I’m a survivor, and after almost 2 hours of progressing through water with the lyrics “we’ve got a long ways to go and a short time to get there, we’re gonna do what they say can’t be done”- I was one of the last 10 people out of the water and ready to make up some ground! 😅
Thanks to @tyler_veerman and his dad I was able to borrow a super nice bike for the bike portion, and even tho I couldn’t figure out how to shift the gears, fully enjoyed the 100+ with almost 6k feet of elevation gain and a max speed of 41.5 mph 
Couldn’t feel my legs for the first 3 miles of the run, but covered my first official road marathon distance to finish in the top 35% overall, 12th in age group which would’ve put me into Kona world champs if I had any interest in swimming that distance again. 

Enjoyed the challenge of figuring out a handful of new sports and doing something I’ve always wanted to do but didn’t always consider possible for me 

#ironman #ironwoman @ironmantri

Had the best weekend out at @highlonesome100! 💯 miler #15 for me started with a one handed cartwheel 35 miles in, was full of some nonstop amazing views, had a solid 30 struggle miles, and finished with a bunch of my favorite people waiting for me at the finish line! ❤️ 

Thanks to @altrarunning for all their support this year, @tamara_dahill @benkruse @ryan.quinn.maguire @mark_coolya and @laura_joch for the biggest and best crew I’ve had yet, and @mile90photo for the awesome race photos! 

And got a nice recovery hike up La Plata Peak the following day for my first 3x summit of a 14’er ⛰️

Brought the ultra legs out again this weekend and they were ready to play! @starvationxtri was one of the toughest races I’ve done in a while- between the dark swim, almost 10k’ of elevation gain on the bike, and finishing with a trail marathon with another 6k’ of climbing, it took a lot to get this one done! Finished 🥇 female and 4th overall, landing me a spot in the Norseman @nxtri next year 

Always grateful for a day in the mountains getting to explore and challenge myself. I had thoughts both of “this is the only ironman distance I’ll ever do from now on” and “I’m definitely never coming back” throughout the day- we’ll see which one ends up winning out, but for now one more week of ultra before taking a little break for until September. 

Thank you @ironcowboyjames and @roblescasey and team for making this happen- and @williamson_troy and @bodie_davis for being a fantastic crew! 

And thanks @austen_alex for the pic! 🤩

I am an athlete, and I love to compete and race, but more than that, I am a person. I am not my achievements, or my accomplishments- or my many failures and shortcomings- I’m who I am to the people around me, the people I love, the people I hope to inspire and encourage. 

This finish line reminded me most of that- I didn’t win, but in my little nanny babes’ eyes- just by finishing, they’re pretty sure I won. They may never understand or appreciate the things I do, and that’s okay. 

But I know that by continuing to challenge myself, by doing things that make me grow and learn and working towards any dream I can come up with, I’m a better person to those around me, and that’s exactly why I’m going to keep doing all the things- I want to be challenged and do things that bring me joy, not just so I can say I did them- but so that I can be the best version of me to anyone I come in contact with ❤️ 

#medalmonday from last weekend at @highlonesome100, one of my favorite finish lines of all time. 

📸: @mile90photo

Hard to believe this past weekend was my 6th year competing in @gritgamesocr by @gritfitnessocr in south Texas. 

This event through all its variations has always challenged me in every way, and this year was no exception. 

The biggest difference this year, is that Texas and Grit are no longer “home” for me, and haven’t been for over a year now! While Colorado has been good to me, and I’ve excelled and grown as an athlete and human- it’s the years of grueling workouts and unreal heat that built me mentally and physically into the athlete I am today. ❤️ 

Was so rewarding to come out with the win against the strongest field of badass ladies we’ve seen yet, and spend a weekend enjoying places and people that were home to me in a very foundational time in my life. 

Can’t thank the @the.coach.kenny and @gritfitnessocr enough for the community that saw my very beginning days as an athlete and still shows up to challenge and support me and so many others in our journeys towards our highest potential 💪🏽 

Best photos always, thanks to @imagesbyjack and @theocrreport! 

#gritgames #2023 #grit #guts #fitness #home

“Real toughness is living in the nuance and complexity of the environment, bodies, and minds we inhabit…. Real toughness is about acceptance: of who you are, what you're going through, and the discomfort that often comes with it. It's living in that place of tension so that the needed space can be created to find the best path forward.” (- @stevemagness in “Do Hard Things”)

As someone who’s put myself through a handful of tough and challenging things, I feel like I’ve developed a level of toughness, both mentally and physically- but reading this book has made me more aware and conscious of the process of being and becoming tough. Was a great read, especially through a series of ultra weekends to both practice and process a lot of the ideas and concepts he wrote about!

📸: @jchapell

Tuesday was a 2 yr old ruck up to Mt Bierstadt, and today was a 28 mile bike to the summit of Mt Evans! 🧗🏼‍♀️🚵🏼‍♀️

This is my why. This is why I seek health and fitness and push to do the most with my time always. I’m not always trying to win things or set new records. But I’m always wanting to squeeze the most I possibly can out of life, trying new things and making special memories with people I love the most 🥰 

“Life is an adventure. It's absolutely filled with opportunity. But it's up to you to embrace those opportunities fully and completely in all of ther majestic, unnerving, and invigorating uncertainty…. “I embrace the uncertainty." This one simple statement can completely change the way you live, moment to moment. The only thing that's guaranteed in life is that it's uncertain. The only thing we know is that we know
nothing.”

Life is in the living, in the experiencing. Go try something new and live a little more fully this week! 🤗 

#athlete #human #nanny #life #colorado #14ers #co14ers

If I disappear to the mountains and never come back it’s because I found a backpacking cat and don’t need anything else in life. 

Maybe not, but seeing Maxine @alwayschoosehappy (2 days in a row!) was the perfect way to start my week getting lost in the mountains. 😻

Covered 100+ miles, summited 10 new 14’ers with some fun traverses, met lots of other adventurers, drank a lot of mountain water, slept in my car, read 2 books, and took zero showers. 
Saw all the deer, elk, marmots, and mountain goats- but also a porcupine and some otters! 

Reluctantly returning to civilization now, but only to go run Hurricane 100k in Hurricane, WV on Saturday! 💯 🏃🏼‍♀️

Took the new hair for a spin last weekend, turns out I really might be lighter and faster! 🏃🏼‍♀️ 

Can’t thank @fortitude187 and @emilee.kate (and Aspen! 👧🏻) enough for a both exhausting and refreshing weekend in West Virginia at the @meeks_mountain_trails Hurricane 100k! 

These two did such a great job of making sure I had everything I could possibly need from the moment I stepped out of the airport, and I got to see their community in action putting on a great event that helped a lot of people push comfort zones. 

Beautiful trails, beautiful people, so grateful for the places and interactions that running has brought into my life 🤗 

And always lucky to have the best shoes @altrarunning #altrarunningcrew and best socks @mudgear in the game taking good care of me and keeping me on the trails!

📸: @ecam44 

#running #ultrarunning #100k #meeksmountaintrail

My goal in fitness and health is to be the strongest, fastest, healthiest version of me. 
Races help bring that out of me 
But health is also mental and emotional. 

What’s the point of gym workouts and high intensity 
If I’m not also able to spend long hours and full days in my body and mind, whether in the mountains or day to day life 
I think sometimes we get so busy checking boxes we forget to check in with ourselves

“As you've probably noticed, when you do try to stay in your comfort zone, you never truly feel comfortabe.
There's always that nagging feeling that you could be doing more. There's always that desire for a life that's better than the one you have now.
The more we try to stay comfortable today, the more uncomfortable we'll be tomorrow. There really is no destination, there is only exploring, exploring, and exploring.”

In 2019, the Barkley Fall Classic, arguanly one of the toughest 50ks out there, schemed up by Laz as a golden ticket race into the Barkley Marathons, was my first “mountain” trail race 

In 2020, I placed second overall female
 
In 2023, I’m finally back- and ready to get uncomfortable and explore for the day! 🏃🏼‍♀️🌲🐀 

#bfc #barkley #barkleymarathons #2023

I came to the Barkley Fall Classic this year planning to win, and knowing I could- and while this was the race of a lifetime, it really took all I had to finish well. 
My half a dozen Yellowjacket stings on my arms/neck/ear while headed up the second big climb of the day were quickly overshadowed by ending up in the front pack going down Ratjaw- a power line cut straight down the side of the mountain, about a mile long, and completely overgrown with saw briars. Legs and arms were pretty scratched up and stinging in a whole different way by the time I made it to the bottom! 
From there- after a quick jog through the Brushy State Prison- the other 2 power line climbs and descents went much more quickly- and then I was headed back up Ratjaw, making it the final climb before a several mile descent down to the finish. 
I knew Andrea Larson, defending 2x champ, was nearby- we’d descended Ratjaw together- but I thought I’d put enough space on her to hopefully be safe. Until she popped up right behind me right as I got to the top! 
Her comment of “well, looks like we have us a race!” as we headed down from the final checkpoint to start that descent to the finish was exactly what I needed to send it on the last downhill. Ended up putting a several minute gap on her before wading across the creek and into the finish line in 9:44:02 in 3rd overall and earning my Golden Ticket 🎫 to the Barkley Marathons! 

During those last few miles, this song came to mind and made me smile. Don’t ever give up on your dreams, goals, crazy ideas, any of it. Things rarely work out the way we plan or expect. But more often or not- you’ll end up right where you belong 🤗 

Dream on
Even when you're afraid all your dreams may be gone
Just dream on
When the world says you're crazy just tell them they're wrong and dream on
To infinity and far beyond
Maybe they'll take you fabulous places
Maybe you'll wakeup right where you belong

Ready to go “where dreams go to die” in 2024! #barkleymarathons

I had a week off work over Labor Day and got to spend it camping, running, and hiking in the mountains! 

I made it up Maroon peak, North Maroon peak, Wetterhorn, Uncompahgre, Sunshine, Redcloud, El Diente, Mount Wilson, Wilson peak, and Mt Sneffels bringing me to a total of 40 out of the 58 14’ers (peaks over 14k’) in Colorado! 

And an excerpt that really stuck out from the book I read while out there:
“The only difference between you and the person who's living the life you want is that they're doing it. 
They've built that life, and they're living it.
They're not smarter, more mindful, stronger, or any of that stuff. 
They don't have anything you don't. 
The only difference is that successful people don't wait.
They're not waiting for the "right" moment. 
They don't wait for inspiration to strike or for some cosmic event to force them to action. They get up and they do, and they try, and they fail even before they may feel "ready." They're flying the airplane while they're building it. 
If it falls out of the sky, they'll piece it back together and try again.
Your internal condition means nothing. 
It's just another excuse that you give yourself to stay out of the risky zones of life. 

The problem is, those risky zones ARE life! The rest is just existing.”

A new episode of The Everyday Ultra Podcast with Kris Rugloski sharing about her win at the Barkley Fall Classic is now available on all platforms!

You’ve likely heard of the Barkley Marathons; but have you heard of the Barkley Fall Classic? It’s the sister race of the infamous, longer race that everyone knows, but is brutal in its own right.

Kris Rugloski is an endurance athelte for Altra who specializes in ultrarunning, obstacle course racing, and HYROX. She is a World’s Toughest World Champion, HYROX Champion, and has been on the podium of tons of ultramarathons, making her one of the most accomplished hybrid athletes in the sport.

In this episode, Kris shares about her win at the Barkley Classic, what allows her to be successful in both ultrarunning and OCR, and her approach to keeping discipline in her life.
